{
  "text": "Finally, we create a route table for the private subnets. This route table has a default route pointing to the NAT gateway instead of the Internet gateway. This means all internet-bound traffic from private subnets goes through the NAT gateway, which provides the secure outbound access we discussed. Notice there's no route that allows inbound traffic from the internet. That's the security benefit. We'll associate this route table with both private subnets, completing our secure network architecture. Now you have a production-ready VPC with public subnets for internet-facing C or Clakestack. Bon buck-bawds! W-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w-w",
